TITLE: Netherlands and Japan Said to Join U.S. in Curbing China’s Access to Chip Tech
SUMMARY: A new agreement is expected to expand the reach of U.S. technology restrictions on China issued last year.

TITLE: When Private Equity Came for the Toddler Gyms
SUMMARY: The same playbook that has notched high returns acquiring things like foreclosed homes and highway rest stops is being tested by a family-oriented franchise.

TITLE: Consumer Spending Fell Again in December
SUMMARY: Fresh data offered more detail on how shoppers retrenched at the end of 2022.

TITLE: A Closely Watched Measure of Inflation Slowed in December
SUMMARY: The Personal Consumption Expenditures price index climbed 5 percent from a year earlier, slower than the reading last month.

TITLE: Biden Hammers Republicans on the Economy, With Eye on 2024
SUMMARY: The president has found a welcome foil in a new conservative House majority and its tax and spending plans, sharpening a potential re-election message.

TITLE: With Layoffs, Retailers Aim to Be Safe Rather Than Sorry (Again)
SUMMARY: Companies that ramped up hiring in areas like technology over the past few years are cutting back as customers slow their spending.

TITLE: U.S. Economy Grew at 2.9% Annual Rate in Fourth Quarter
SUMMARY: The continued growth in the fourth quarter showed the resilience of consumers and businesses in the face of inflation and rising interest rates.

TITLE: Why The Times Is Resuming its Emphasis on Annualized Figures for GDP
SUMMARY: The pandemic shock is no longer producing exceptional economic gyrations.

TITLE: California Voters to Decide on Regulating Fast-Food Industry
SUMMARY: Pre-empting a law signed last year, business groups forced a ballot initiative on state oversight of wages and working conditions.

TITLE: Climate Change May Bring New Era of Trade Wars, as E.U. and U.S. Spar
SUMMARY: Countries are pursuing new solutions to try to mitigate climate change. More trade fights are likely to come hand in hand.

TITLE: Walmart Raises Starting Wages for Store Workers
SUMMARY: The retail giant said the minimum wages for those employees would range from $14 to $19 an hour, up from $12 to $18 an hour.

TITLE: What’s Behind All Those Tech Layoffs? A New Economic Reality
SUMMARY: Rock-bottom rates were the secret engine fueling $1 billion start-ups and virtual attempts to conquer the physical world. But in 2023, reality bites.

TITLE: Inflation Is Cooling, Leaving America Asking: What Comes Next?
SUMMARY: After six months of declines, inflation seems to be turning a corner. But the road back to normal is an uncertain one.

TITLE: Families Struggle as Pandemic Program Offering Free School Meals Ends
SUMMARY: A federal benefit guaranteeing free school meals to millions more students has expired as food prices have risen. Many families are feeling the pinch.

TITLE: How the U.S. Government Amassed $31 Trillion in Debt
SUMMARY: Two decades of tax cuts, recession responses and bipartisan spending fueled more borrowing — contributing $25 trillion to the total and setting the stage for another federal showdown.

TITLE: Fed Rate Increases Have ‘A Ways to Go,’ Top Official Says
SUMMARY: Christopher Waller, a Federal Reserve governor, said he favored a quarter-point move. Many of his colleagues agree — or haven’t ruled it out.

TITLE: New Orleans Port Expansion Shows Optimism on Future of Global Trade
SUMMARY: The city that was once the world’s gateway to America is betting it can win in a new and different era of global integration.

TITLE: What Happens Next in the Debt Limit Debate?
SUMMARY: The Treasury Department has started employing “extraordinary measures,” but the path to raising the debt ceiling is likely to be a long one.

TITLE: White House Aims to Reflect the Environment in Economic Data
SUMMARY: The Biden administration has set out to measure the economic value of ecosystems, offering new statistics to weigh in policy decisions.

TITLE: As Fed Nears Next Rate Decision, Its Vice Chair Cites Reasons for Hope
SUMMARY: Lael Brainard, the vice chair of the Federal Reserve, emphasized that non-wage causes had driven inflation in a sweeping speech.
